00:23:02.150 --> 00:23:06.578 align:middle line:90%


00:23:06.578 --> 00:23:12.590 align:middle line:84%
So the previous experiment
with the peas looking for water

00:23:12.590 --> 00:23:17.700 align:middle line:84%
using sound was quite
straightforward.

00:23:17.700 --> 00:23:22.890 align:middle line:84%
The pea was growing
inside a maze,

00:23:22.890 --> 00:23:27.710 align:middle line:84%
which was the shape of
a letter Y upside down.

00:23:27.710 --> 00:23:35.930 align:middle line:84%
And when I just placed real
water at one end of the maze,

00:23:35.930 --> 00:23:40.190 align:middle line:84%
the pea grew its root straight
to it, which is not surprising

00:23:40.190 --> 00:23:44.070 align:middle line:84%
because they use the
humidity gradient to detect

00:23:44.070 --> 00:23:45.650 align:middle line:90%
the source of water.

00:23:45.650 --> 00:23:50.570 align:middle line:84%
Now I then did what we
do with animal studies

00:23:50.570 --> 00:23:52.880 align:middle line:84%
and design a
playback experiment,

00:23:52.880 --> 00:23:56.030 align:middle line:84%
so I actually recorded the
sound of water in the pipe

00:23:56.030 --> 00:23:58.520 align:middle line:84%
and I played it
back by attaching

00:23:58.520 --> 00:24:01.880 align:middle line:84%
a little speaker, a
vibration speaker,

00:24:01.880 --> 00:24:06.720 align:middle line:84%
in an iPod, which would play
back the sound of water.

00:24:06.720 --> 00:24:10.820 align:middle line:84%
And what I found is
that the peas would also

00:24:10.820 --> 00:24:16.550 align:middle line:84%
be able to find the source
of water through the sound

00:24:16.550 --> 00:24:19.700 align:middle line:84%
even when water really
is nowhere to be found.

00:24:19.700 --> 00:24:29.980 align:middle line:90%


